<br>
If the thought of being totally group dependent once again appeals to you, try grouping at the other extreme from where you have been so far. (Reminds me I should do the same some day and play an enc <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) <br>
<br>
Why play a warrior? Because they're great fun of course. Those empty spell slots and the complete lack of means of evasion/avoidance will probably make you go crazy at first, but see it as a challenge and as trying something completely different for a change. You will soon become a master of stealth and deception while travelling - ask any warrior!<br>
<br>
As a grouped warrior there is always something going on each moment that involves you. There are times when things get a bit repetitive like with any class. But being a warrior is NOT just pressing autoattack and taunt, like some casters seem to think. As always, there are a lot of subtleties you have to learn about and master gradually. What is a bit different with warriors is that there is very little of the either/or, yes/no, successful/failed skillcheck, resist/stick. Rather, there are typically degrees of everything. That appeals to me.<br>
<br>
Sure, there are a lot of warriors on Brell compared to rogues for instance. Does that mean we have a problem finding groups? Generally no. Try to figure out why.<br>
<br>
When summarizing the role of a warrior, most people use terms like &quot;tanking&quot; or &quot;meat shielding&quot;. Yes, you can take a hit, you are meant to take a hit, and there will be many times when you're ready beg the mobs on your bare knees to smack you instead of the monk, rogue or caster. But just as your role as an enchanter is crowd control, I would say the role of the warrior is rather one of aggro control. That's a more accurate job description. What makes it exciting is that it involves more of developing attentiveness a good sense of judgement than of just hoping for a successful taunt skill check.<br>
<br>
I haven't tried a bard or rogue yet. Monks are great fun because of their class skills. But the actual melee part of hunting is more fun with a warrior, if you ask me. The novelty of dishing out a huge amount of damage wears off pretty quickly.<br>
<br>
Just my opinion on warriors. I hope you enjoy your &quot;serious alt&quot;, regardless of what class he will be. Just a last piece of advice, though, based on experience with my own and others alts - a word on twinking: <br>
<br>
It's fun to twink and a little twinking helps getting through the boring low lvls, the period when your class hasn't separated itself enough from others yet. But people who twink too much don't learn their class specific essentials enough, so if you're making a serious alt you should be careful. Once you've outgrown a twink equipment you will feel like you hit a rock wall and you start thinking that it's because you're not twinked enough. So you twink some more, which only serves to escalate the real problem and postpone the inevitable - you simply suck at your class! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Learning and improving is half the fun, socializing makes up for the rest. But who am I to tell you that. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
